<h3>Hemp FACT #56- FAMM3 </h3>

<p>Date: 95-03-11 10:40:05 EDT </p>

<p>From: ADBryan </p>

<p><b>The Cost of Mandatory Minimums</b> </p>

<p>What do mandatory minimums cost taxpayers? </p>

<p>The average cost of incarcerating a federal inmate is $20,804
per year. (Bureau of Prisons, 1994) </p>

<p>Sixty-two percent of federal inmates are drug offenders, and
half of them are first offenders. (Bureau of Prisons testimony,
May 1993). </p>

<p>To feed, clothe, house, and guard the 54,000 federal drug
inmates costs taxpayers over $1.1 billion per year. </p>

<p>The Bureaus of Prisons budget increased by 1,350 percent
between 1982 and FY 1993, to a total of $2.3 billion annually.
(National Drug Control Strategy Budget Summary, 1992). </p>

<p>States spend more of their budgets on justice programs (6.4%)
than on housing and he environment (3.8) and nearly as much as on
health care (8.9%) (Bureau of Justice Statistics, September,
1992). </p>

<p>It costs more to send a person to prison for four years than
it does to send him to a private university for four years,
including tuition, fees, room, board, books and supplies. (Bureau
of Prisons). </p>

